const faqItems = [
  {
    q: "What's the minimum volume a roastery needs before starting a wholesale program?",
    a: "There's no hard minimum, but a practical threshold is the ability to roast 50–100 lbs per week consistently beyond your own retail and direct-to-consumer needs. Below that, wholesale demand can outpace production capacity and create service failures that damage the accounts you're trying to build. Most roasters launch wholesale programs when they have 2–3x production capacity beyond current demand."
  },
  {
    q: "How should wholesale coffee pricing be structured?",
    a: "Wholesale pricing in specialty coffee typically runs 20–35% below retail bag pricing, with volume discounts at defined thresholds. Set your floor price by working backward from your fully loaded cost of goods — green coffee, roasting overhead, packaging, and delivery — plus a minimum margin that makes the program financially viable. Never set wholesale pricing based on what competitors charge; set it based on your own cost structure."
  },
  {
    q: "What's included in a good wholesale coffee program?",
    a: "A complete wholesale program includes: competitive pricing with defined minimums and volume tiers, a sample program for prospective accounts, barista training and extraction support, equipment consultation or partnerships, seasonal menu guidance, and a dedicated point of contact for service issues. The programs that retain accounts longest treat training and support as core to the offer, not add-ons."
  },
  {
    q: "How do I compete with larger roasters for wholesale accounts?",
    a: "Smaller roasters almost always win on relationship depth and service responsiveness — the things that larger operations sacrifice as they scale. A café owner who can call their roaster directly and get an answer wins over the café owner who submits a support ticket. Lean into that advantage. Don't try to match larger roasters on price or marketing budget; compete on the things that scale can't buy."
  }
];

